<h1>BA (Hons) Corporate Communications*</h1>

											
																
		
		
		



		
			<span class="h4_red">UCAS Code:</span> P900 BA/CC<br />	
		
			<span class="h4_red">Duration:</span> Four years full-time<br />	
		
			<span class="h4_red">Number of Places:</span> 40<br />	
<br />
		
			<a href="#Intro">Introduction</a><br />	
		
			<a href="#Themes">Core Themes</a><br />	
		
		
		
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
			
			
					
			
			
			
					
			
					
			
					
			<a href="#Entry">Entry Routes</a><br />	
		
		
<br />		

		
		
		
			
		

		
			
			
		

		
		
<br/>


			<h3 id="Intro">Introduction</h3><b>Key Features</b><br />â¢	Focus on professional skills and a creative approach to Corporate Communication<br />â¢	Development of excellent communication skills sought by employers <br /><br />An organisationâs reputation, profitability, and even its survival, can depend on its success in communicating its goals and objectives to its public and its own members. Effective communication, closely linked to business objectives and strategies, is essential if organisations are to inform and influence external stakeholders including their customers, and to harness the efforts of all their members towards the successful accomplishment of organisational objectives.  <br /><br />The BA (Hons) Corporate Communication programme meets the needs of organisations for multi-skilled and highly effective corporate communication professionals.  This highly vocational programme integrates the development of professional communication and practical implementation skills with a detailed knowledge of the critical issues facing organisations that require particular attention to the development of corporate identity and the management of corporate reputation. <br /> <br />Corporate Communication specialists are advocates for and advisors to organisations in managing the complex communications that take place between organisations and their external and internal audiences.  To do this, they must understand the complexities of communication within organisations, and the need for organisations to represent themselves externally to a range of stakeholders.  They are involved both in representing the organisation and keeping the organisation aware of public views and attitudes.  They are likely to be required to draft press releases, manage media contacts, and arrange and conduct programmes of internal and external communications in times of development and times of crisis.  They will be involved in the development of communication plans and policies, in the design of appropriate messages, and in the management of projects to communicate those messages.  They must demonstrate creativity, good judgement, sound and contemporary business knowledge, as well as consistently high-level communication skills<br />Corporate Communication graduates will be able to work in communication departments of both business and non-profit organisations including government agencies, and to freelance in a range of consultancy roles.   They will also be valued recruits to more general business roles in which confident communication skills and knowledge of a range of communication approaches is required.<br /><br /><b>*At the current time this course is still under development  for September 2007 and is therefore subject to change and final approval</b><br/><br/>	
		
		

			<h3 id="Themes">Core Themes</h3><b>What you study<br />Stage 1</b><br />Stage one provides an essential background in core business areas as well as fundamental IT and communication skills. Students who successfully complete stage one and do not proceed with further study will be eligible for the award of CertHE Business and Management.<br /><b>Stage 2</b><br />At stage two you will study the role of Corporate Communications in contributing to organisational objectives, and the processes of communication in both theory and contemporary practice.  You will also start to build a skill portfolio that demonstrates your skills across a range of professional communication areas.<br /><b>Stage 3</b><br />At stage three you will investigate further the strategic context of corporate communication, and develop your skills in planning and managing corporate communication projects.  You will work on projects â independently and as a member of a team - and you will present your ideas and solutions in a range of formats.<br /><b>Stage 4</b><br />At stage four you will take both your professional skills and your knowledge of corporate communication to an advanced level, developing and presenting plans for corporate communication in a range of different scenarios, including crisis management and the development of corporate brands. You will present your own plans and comment on those of your colleagues in the context of organisational challenge.<br /><br /><b>How you learn and are assessed</b><br />The programme combines the development of detailed knowledge of corporate communication and its business context with the development of communication and practical skills.  So there is considerable emphasis on a workshop approach, as well as on lectures, seminars and tutorials.  You will produce personal portfolios, plan projects in groups and individually, analyse and comment on contemporary cases in corporate communication, and develop strategies and plans for specific situations; your assessment will combined traditional examination and essay with demonstrations of your developing skills and the presentation of projects and plans.<br /><br />	
		
		
		

		

		
